00:43:57.860 --> 00:43:59.340
Like the which Hegel question.

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:03.300
Like that's, to me, when it gets to that point, none of these thinkers is anything.

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:04.240
Yeah.

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:04.520
Right?

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:09.660
So precisely for that reason, I mean, like go back to the concept of play.

00:44:09.660 --> 00:44:13.460
You know, there's the sort of like the response or the stylistic of play.

00:44:14.060 --> 00:44:19.140
And, you know, in many ways, you know, the point, I mean, Derrida doesn't seem to be making

00:44:19.140 --> 00:44:22.380
the point, go off and play, go off and be ludic.

00:44:22.460 --> 00:44:25.280
It seems more that play is a...

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:25.780
The condition.

00:44:26.780 --> 00:44:32.860
Yeah, is a, you know, a condition of the very possibility of something like conceptuality.

00:44:32.860 --> 00:44:36.760
Like play is a condition of the possibility of something like sincerity.

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:46.180
And in fact, sincerity, nostalgia, labor are all themselves styles of play in that they sort

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:51.500
of like, like they run themselves out and like along a different, like a differential route

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:55.080
and make and remake, you know, things in the, in their path.

00:44:55.160 --> 00:45:00.860
So like we have to, in some ways, I think, differentiate between two senses of play.

00:45:00.960 --> 00:45:06.580
Like one is that structural dimension of play that is unavoidable, even in its perceived, you

00:45:06.580 --> 00:45:07.400
know, oppositions.

00:45:07.720 --> 00:45:13.980
And then another more like stylistic play as an orientation that, you know, John, you seem

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:19.160
to be saying, you know, I, I, like, is the, is the, is the kind of playlist.

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:21.700
I don't want to listen to the nostalgia track.

00:45:21.780 --> 00:45:24.460
I don't want to listen to the heavy metal labor.

00:45:24.600 --> 00:45:29.060
I don't want to listen to, you know, I, you know, I want some, I want Calypso.

00:45:29.340 --> 00:45:33.900
But to me, like we have to differentiate between those two senses of play.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:40.120
And, and, you know, my presumption is that Deleuze sort of, you know, gives you that, that,

00:45:40.120 --> 00:45:46.160
that playlist in a way that Derrida just shows you that you have to pull your list.

00:45:47.040 --> 00:45:47.700
Right, right.

00:45:48.380 --> 00:45:53.640
And that the list is our, like the playlist of play is our, is itself made up.

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:57.220
Like the very distinction you made between two senses of play is a product of play.

00:45:57.660 --> 00:46:03.460
So, yeah, like I, I agree the most rigorous scholastic fucking Spinozistic argument of

00:46:03.460 --> 00:46:10.820
axiom, theorem, whatever, is as much a demonstration of the play of difference as some sort of

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:14.740
ludic, you know, like Derridian sort of play on words.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:14.940
Right.

00:46:15.020 --> 00:46:17.940
And, and to be quite honest with you, that's why I don't like the word play.

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:18.880
Right.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:22.440
Like I, I don't like, I don't like the word labor, but I don't like the word play either.

00:46:22.440 --> 00:46:23.760
Like I like dance.

00:46:24.460 --> 00:46:24.860
Right.

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:27.140
Like, I mean, I, I, or music or whatever.

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:33.320
Like to me, those are, those terms, again, they just sort of hook, hook better for me

00:46:33.320 --> 00:46:37.340
and they don't bring them because play brings with it that sort of sense of like, oh, let's

00:46:37.340 --> 00:46:40.880
go do, uh, you know, let's go do something fun.

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:47.480
And it's like, no, no, no, this is play is the condition for like the most focused, narrow,

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:58.040
you know, uh, well-structured essay as much as it is panorama, you know, so the conceptual plot, I mean, that, and to me, like, this is

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:03.940
what, this is what Derrida is just absolutely fucking extraordinary at, right?

00:47:03.940 --> 00:47:12.940
Like the, the sort of careful and meticulous movement through both the dance steps and the undermining of the conditions of the dance steps.

00:47:13.180 --> 00:47:17.180
And, and yet it's still like extraordinary to witness.

00:47:17.180 --> 00:47:18.700
For me, it's just extraordinary.

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:29.460
Like, again, it's, it's just like lines of thinking when we, if we call them a playlist, it's, that's, it just feels so external in that sense of like, hey, I play this music and I feel good.

00:47:29.460 --> 00:47:42.200
And this is more like, what is the, what is the means of thinking that allow, like this allows my, my body, my brain to like, to head in directions that those other things don't.

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:52.820
Um, but this is what, like Derrida's style of play, I don't see, I, I very rarely find anything ludic about Derrida's writing.

00:47:52.820 --> 00:47:58.820
And in terms of its sort of like humor, I, it's generally, you know, quite dry, you know, like his jokes.

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:14.760
But, but like his style of, of play seems to be one of, you know, absolute commitment to rigor without mastery, which is, you know, like, I mean, you know, you're right.

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:36.520
He's not fun with puns at all, but he is constantly sort of like, as he traces a, um, uh, a term, a binary, a dynamic or whatever else, like he's constantly finding these juncture points, you know, like, like the traces of sort of like past interaction of forces, you could say.

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:39.680
Um, or like residues of interactions of forces.

00:48:40.340 --> 00:48:49.680
Uh, and then like, just literally, he's just taking a thread and then following it to its next knot and finding three other threads that attach to that.

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:50.160
That's right.

00:48:50.600 --> 00:49:09.500
And like that work is sometimes funny, sometimes it's clever, sometimes it's witty, but like, it doesn't seem to be Derrida's imposition of some kind of prior humor or like ludic sensibility so much as it is just like sometimes following the thread is fucking funny.

00:49:09.940 --> 00:49:12.820
I mean, I think it's also just his style of writing too.

00:49:12.900 --> 00:49:20.220
I mean, a lot of it feels like improvisation in the, in the moment, like where he moves from one paragraph to the next or makes these qualifications.

00:49:20.660 --> 00:49:29.080
It almost feels like the best first draft that somebody could come up with because there's not this, it's not a package, right?

00:49:29.100 --> 00:49:33.560
Where you get the neat thesis statement and then the repetition of the thesis statement at the end.

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:39.660
I mean, he's literally following his train of thought and then complicating it each and with each and every turn.

00:49:39.740 --> 00:49:54.580
So you, you get a sense for his movement of thinking like in real time, like you can see where he made the realization or the kind of intuition and then follows up on it in the actual place where he made that, like, at least it feels almost.

00:49:55.060 --> 00:50:09.540
But that's exactly why I don't find his, his writing to be so propositional because like when you are sort of following that sort of stream of consciousness, one of the sort of, you know, revision moves as a, you know, in composition is then to take

00:50:09.540 --> 00:50:18.460
take those moves out so that what is rewhat remains is just sort of like the positive claims that one has, you know, like positioned in there.

00:50:18.460 --> 00:50:23.460
So it's like, you know, me and my thinking have been left out and only, you know, like the knowledge has gotten there.

00:50:23.460 --> 00:50:28.220
And then, you know, there's transitions between the logical steps, but it's all been filtered.

00:50:28.220 --> 00:50:29.100
And, and you're right.

00:50:29.160 --> 00:50:39.780
I think that Derrida doesn't, he doesn't run it through a purifying filter that the, the, the, the rigor is all imminent, like to, to the movement of thinking itself.

00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:50.520
So the moves are what matter and any given proposition is, you know, like valuable only insofar as it gestures you off to the next thing.

00:50:51.060 --> 00:50:51.420
Right.

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:55.100
So just to, I mean, like that's all on the first paragraph.

00:50:55.100 --> 00:51:04.300
Like I must stay here now that today's discourse will be less a justification of, and even less an apology for this silent lapse in spelling than a kind of insistent intensification of its play.

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:04.700
Yeah.

00:51:04.740 --> 00:51:06.440
Like that's, that's what this is going to be.

00:51:06.500 --> 00:51:08.400
I'm just going to like, I'm going to write for a while.

00:51:08.600 --> 00:51:11.560
I'm going to think through the various movements.

00:51:12.020 --> 00:51:16.860
But I really like, there's a point that has really, really stuck with me over the years.

00:51:16.860 --> 00:51:25.120
Well, John, can I just read the next little bit there, like that, that language of the sheaf, which, you know, it's just turning to a Middle English.

00:51:26.220 --> 00:51:28.780
But see, that's the thing, that's the thing that he does all the time.

00:51:28.840 --> 00:51:37.000
He takes obscure esoteric etymological terms and shows that they're like absolutely central to any way of thinking about anything.

00:51:37.640 --> 00:51:39.320
Which, which could be anything, right?

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:41.800
But it's just that it's sheaf, right?

00:51:41.800 --> 00:51:46.060
The blow in Plato or whatever, like it's always just this word that, yeah.

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:58.060
Well, but that one makes more sense because that one is so interestingly attached to the mark of the writing, the, like this one, like as far as I can tell, the sheaf is just like a bundle of corn or a bundle of grain.

00:51:58.380 --> 00:52:03.700
And then, you know, sort of it gets generalized out to like a bundle of, or assemblage of anything.

00:52:04.800 --> 00:52:07.720
But it's like, I insist upon this word sheaf for two reasons.

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:18.960
On the one hand, I will not be concerned as I might have been with describing a history and narrating its stages, text by text, context by context, demonstrating the economy that each time imposed this graphic disorder.

00:52:19.340 --> 00:52:22.000
Rather, I'll be concerned with the general system of this economy.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:42.300
On the other hand, the word sheaf seems to mark more appropriately that the assemblage to be proposed has the complex structure of a weaving and interlacing, which permits the different threads and different lines of meaning or of force to go off again in different directions, just as it is always ready to tie itself up with others.

00:52:42.300 --> 00:53:05.260
I love that phrase because it gets around the problem of, like, you know, systemic order as opposed to chaos, where like either there's an archie that sort of like top-down directs and organizes or from the middle out organizes the body around it, or it's just the chaos of relationships.

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:32.080
Like, like, in this notion of a weaving, an interlacing, like, there are, it's more like a heterogeneous collection of logics of organizational forces that, like, it's only, like, this, you know, this line takes and appropriates that line and organize it in relationship to itself,

00:53:32.080 --> 00:53:45.380
which only then means that it has the potentiality to connect to other things according to different logics or being, or it makes itself more or less vulnerable to be taken up by different threads in different logics.

00:53:45.640 --> 00:53:51.640
Like, it's more likely to get picked up by these kinds of things and less likely to get picked up by these other kinds of things.

00:53:51.760 --> 00:54:08.400
And so, like, that's not chaotic, but it's certainly not governed by a transcendental logic either, which is why that, you know, like, and the very movement, the very sort of, like, evolutionary, you know, mutation of this sheaf of this assemblage of things.

00:54:09.160 --> 00:54:21.100
Like, it has a history, and, like, I mean, not a history, but, like, it has histories, and, like, but it's certainly not chaotic.

00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:23.040
Lost my train of thought there for a second.

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:34.900
It reminds me, I mean, for me, the concept that has always helped me think that is in the Rhizome chapter for Deleuze, where he says the notion of ontological multiplicity is not a given.

00:54:34.900 --> 00:54:39.080
It's a constructivism, which is multiplicity has to be made.

00:54:39.240 --> 00:54:47.680
It's not just there, you know, it's like, but that's all that's ever getting produced, right, is multiplicity is a production.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.380
You know, you have to be careful with each of those words.

00:54:50.400 --> 00:54:52.820
It's not just out there in the world, right?

00:54:52.880 --> 00:54:57.460
I mean, so that's kind of a key part of both Deleuze's and Derrida's project, right?

00:54:57.460 --> 00:55:04.760
Like you were saying with somebody who took up the trace as kind of an ontotheological principle and origin, where it's explicitly not that.

00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:06.040
And it's the same in Deleuze.

00:55:06.520 --> 00:55:11.820
Assemblages are made, right, constitutively, which is a difficult thing to think, obviously.

00:55:11.820 --> 00:55:12.860
It's a very difficult thing.

00:55:12.960 --> 00:55:23.620
Like, I understand why the guy wants the ontotheological, because he then has an argument, which is, ah, I figured out the origin for all of these differences, and it is the trace.

00:55:23.900 --> 00:55:26.500
And it's like, you know, yes and no, right?

00:55:26.640 --> 00:55:27.840
Like, that's the only answer.

00:55:28.180 --> 00:55:32.320
And in fact, the trace is the condition of possibility for thinking origins.

00:55:33.020 --> 00:55:38.740
So it's like, it diagnoses the simplified interpretation of itself.

00:55:39.060 --> 00:55:39.960
Yes, it does.

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:41.120
And enables.

00:55:41.400 --> 00:55:42.440
Like, it produces that.

00:55:42.640 --> 00:55:47.540
So that, and that's, I mean, to me, that's deconstruction in a nutshell, right?

00:55:47.620 --> 00:55:52.620
Like, it's both, the condition of possibility is simultaneously the condition of impossibility, right?

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:59.420
Like, it's right there in the kind of, quote-unquote, misreading of Derrida's trace as an origin.

00:56:00.380 --> 00:56:00.960
Well, yeah.

00:56:01.520 --> 00:56:03.500
And the reason it's not, no, go ahead.

00:56:03.760 --> 00:56:03.980
Sorry.

00:56:04.120 --> 00:56:15.960
I was just going to say, I like this schemata as well, because it helps really situate something like a, like, systemic, logical, you know, based off of the logic of identity thinking.

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:33.080
Like, that sort of archaic style transcendent thought, which, you know, you could not say is opposed to this multiplicity to this, this weaving, this interlacing of sheaves, whatever else, is that it has to, like, if multiplicities are built, so are homogeneities.

00:56:33.780 --> 00:56:33.860
Right?

00:56:33.860 --> 00:56:43.140
So, you know, like, I mean, I think you could point to any sort of binary, you know, man, woman, nature, culture, whatever, whatever.

00:56:43.660 --> 00:56:53.300
And it's like, you know, it's a particular alliance, it's a particular sort of, like, interweaving of a few different threads that then starts to, like, replicate itself.

00:56:53.400 --> 00:56:57.780
It starts to replicate everything else around it in its image.

00:56:57.780 --> 00:57:19.400
And what I really like about Derrida, maybe even more than Deleuze in this sense, is that he, like, he will follow the movement of any one of those sort of archaic alliances and follow them until they become unrecognizable to themselves.

00:57:19.400 --> 00:57:25.300
To the point where, like, they cannot achieve any kind of stability.

00:57:25.580 --> 00:57:28.640
And we think of them as these, like, stable-making devices.

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:34.720
But they're really much more like cancers.

00:57:34.720 --> 00:57:35.900
Performative enactments.

00:57:36.640 --> 00:57:44.960
Performative enactments that, you know, like, it doesn't even make sense to think about them as having some kind of intention of stabilizing.

00:57:44.960 --> 00:57:53.300
It's just more like it's a direction, it's a style of moving in a direction that has no end.

00:57:53.720 --> 00:58:12.260
That will, you know, like, any part of the path will look unrecognizable to any other part of the path without doing a whole lot of, you know, very, very careful tracing of, you know, how, you know, like, one moment of man-woman, you know, is connected to another moment of man-woman.

00:58:12.260 --> 00:58:17.840
Because we all know that, like, there are moments of man-woman that look unrecognizable, you know, to each other.

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:27.240
I mean, I would just say, like, the operation of stabilization in that sense is simply an operation of not paying attention and not thinking.

00:58:27.500 --> 00:58:28.780
That's all it is.

00:58:29.040 --> 00:58:30.920
And we do that all the time.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:39.240
I mean, that's where, you know, that actually returns me to the thing that I really like in the first paragraph that has really stuck with me, oddly, more than anything else in this essay.

00:58:39.240 --> 00:58:44.520
So he's talking, you know, I will speak, therefore, of this initial letter A, and then a few lines down.

00:58:44.660 --> 00:58:51.240
One can always de facto or de jure erase or reduce this lapse of spelling and find it grave or unseemly.

00:58:51.880 --> 00:58:55.340
That is to follow the most ingenuous hypothesis in music.

00:58:55.760 --> 00:59:04.960
So here are a series of ways of reducing the spelling mistake, just like, you know, finding it grave or, like, unseemly, like, oh, that's just so...

00:59:04.960 --> 00:59:07.100
Or finding it funny and clever.

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:15.340
So that's, to me, like, finding it funny and clever is as much a means of reducing it as finding it inappropriate or unacceptable.

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:18.300
Like, and because I'm always on the clever side, right?

00:59:18.380 --> 00:59:22.280
Like, and I'm like, oh, he's calling me out for finding it clever.

00:59:23.520 --> 00:59:36.040
Thus, even if one seeks to pass over such an infraction in silence, the interest that one takes in it can be recognized and situated in advance as prescribed by the mute irony, the inaudible misplacement of this literal permutation.

00:59:36.040 --> 00:59:42.640
So even the action of reducing is itself a deployment of the relation.

00:59:43.160 --> 00:59:47.720
And then this is, it's like, one can always act as if it made no difference, right?

00:59:47.800 --> 00:59:49.840
Like, and I return to that all the time.

00:59:49.920 --> 00:59:50.960
Like, that has so stuck with me.

00:59:51.020 --> 00:59:52.420
Like, one can just ignore it.

00:59:52.920 --> 00:59:54.780
Like, one doesn't have to write an essay.

00:59:55.400 --> 00:59:59.380
One doesn't have to, like, one can ignore any part of it that one wants.

00:59:59.440 --> 01:00:01.520
And that's, like, that's the condition.

01:00:01.660 --> 01:00:03.940
Like, one cannot think about this anymore.

01:00:04.100 --> 01:00:05.040
One can find it clever.

01:00:05.400 --> 01:00:08.220
One can find it annoying, but one cannot think.

01:00:08.340 --> 01:00:12.280
That's always an option on the table for any distinction.

01:00:13.120 --> 01:00:23.080
That not thinking, that not following through, that, you know, whatever you want to call it, is not itself a stagnation, right?

01:00:23.420 --> 01:00:23.880
That's right.

01:00:24.100 --> 01:00:24.540
That's right.

01:00:24.800 --> 01:00:30.740
Because, you know, that is, you know, if we're going to take it seriously, that is a response, then it's an inventive response.

01:00:30.860 --> 01:00:32.520
It changes the thing.

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:34.260
It does something, right?

01:00:34.260 --> 01:00:40.360
Like, even if it's a calcification or homogenization or whatever, it's a doing something.

01:00:40.720 --> 01:00:45.600
One part of the apparatus gets a little bit knotted up, a little bit tighter, and everything else has to respond to it.

01:00:46.080 --> 01:00:46.380
Right.

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:50.620
So, it's, like, that said, one can always act as if it made no difference.

01:00:50.740 --> 01:00:54.360
And also, the next line, because I've written sentences like that in some of my things before.

01:00:54.680 --> 01:00:57.260
It's, like, and there's nothing wrong with that, right?

01:00:57.320 --> 01:01:05.140
There's not, like, there's no reason that one can offer to say that one should think more or that one should, you know, like, there isn't.

01:01:05.240 --> 01:01:08.040
There is just, you do it or you don't do it, right?

01:01:08.160 --> 01:01:12.040
Like, you know, there's no reason why this guy should read deeper on the trace.

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:12.900
There isn't.

01:01:12.980 --> 01:01:13.900
Like, I can't, I mean, whatever.

01:01:14.300 --> 01:01:16.340
There are different styles, and so I can say that.

01:01:16.400 --> 01:01:21.100
I can say, like, well, your reading of the trace ignores this, you know, the complications and whatever.

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:22.480
And that's what we do.

01:01:22.580 --> 01:01:28.340
That's what a, sort of, dialogue between different styles or confrontation of different styles, that's what it is.

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:35.380
But it's not, like, there's not, like, some transcendent reason why he's getting Derrida wrong and that's a problem.

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:37.440
There just isn't, you know.

01:01:38.140 --> 01:01:42.640
And that's actually where, for me, that's where I, sort of, go more towards Deleuze.

01:01:42.740 --> 01:01:50.280
Because I do feel like, for Derrida, there is a sense of, he will say, like, a certain Hegelianism and a certain Heideggerianism and a certain, it's, like,

01:01:50.620 --> 01:01:56.180
he does seem to think that there is, that, for instance, the death metal can't just be changed into the calypso.

01:01:56.520 --> 01:01:58.520
That there's still something death metal-y there.

01:01:58.880 --> 01:02:01.360
And I'm like, I don't think that there is something death metal-y there.

01:02:01.480 --> 01:02:06.160
Like, it's death metal for me, and I don't know how to hear it as calypso, but I believe it's possible.

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:10.560
Like, I believe that you can give me a Hegel that doesn't have a dialectic, for example.

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:18.720
Well, the other way of hearing that, the other way of hearing that isn't that it's, you know, there's something essentially, you know, death metal about it,

01:02:18.740 --> 01:02:21.600
but that the passage, you can't just make it.

01:02:21.740 --> 01:02:24.360
Like, I can't just, like, make it by declaring it.

01:02:24.720 --> 01:02:25.320
Right, that's right.

01:02:25.340 --> 01:02:26.140
I agree with that.

01:02:26.800 --> 01:02:29.000
It has very particular lines of communication.

01:02:29.180 --> 01:02:32.040
Like, calypso and death metal have very particular lines of communication.

01:02:32.220 --> 01:02:32.440
That's right.

01:02:32.440 --> 01:02:39.160
And, you know, like, the play that would be required for that line of transformation would, you know, have to be pretty precise.

01:02:39.160 --> 01:02:39.860
Have to make it.

01:02:40.020 --> 01:02:40.400
That's right.

01:02:40.460 --> 01:02:41.840
You'd have to make it.

01:02:41.880 --> 01:02:42.760
You'd have to assemble it.

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:43.840
You'd have to produce it.

01:02:43.880 --> 01:02:50.820
But it can be done, which is why I have no problem with the idea of Žižek shows you a Hegel that's all about absolute contingency.

01:02:50.960 --> 01:02:59.240
Now, I think probably the distinction is Nate, at some level, goes, well, that's the right Hegel, right?

01:02:59.320 --> 01:03:01.280
And it's like, no, that's not the right Hegel.

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:02.820
That's a more interesting Hegel.

01:03:02.940 --> 01:03:05.720
That's a Hegel that can allow you to do other kinds of things.

01:03:05.900 --> 01:03:14.520
But to me, like, the fact of Hegel being contingency boy is totally unsurprising to me and more interesting.

01:03:14.520 --> 01:03:21.320
It makes my reading of Hegel, like, more compelling in the ways that I think the relationships among many of these thinkers are more compelling.

01:03:21.480 --> 01:03:22.980
So, therefore, I'm all for it.

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:26.040
But it's not because I feel like we got Hegel right.

01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:29.300
I mean, I wouldn't argue, at least outright, that there's a correct reading.

01:03:29.300 --> 01:03:30.700
I don't even know what that means, by the way.

01:03:30.700 --> 01:03:33.780
Let me just say, I don't even know what it would mean to say getting Hegel right.

01:03:34.300 --> 01:03:35.140
Well, I wouldn't either.

01:03:35.360 --> 01:03:53.600
I mean, there's too many, there's too much, I mean, for me, there's too much complexity in Hegel to simply, in any writing, in any author, there's too much diversity in Derrida to simply say he's a materialist rather than a linguist, you know, any of those kind of strict assertions.

01:03:53.600 --> 01:04:03.380
I mean, the only thing I would say is that against the French tradition, which had viable political reasons to go against Hegel, there is a different Hegel.

01:04:03.880 --> 01:04:08.280
And oftentimes, you need a straw man for a project.

01:04:08.700 --> 01:04:10.380
Well, it doesn't have to be a straw man.

01:04:10.480 --> 01:04:16.800
Straw man implies that there is a more complex, fuller something behind the thing that one is attacking.

01:04:16.860 --> 01:04:17.660
It's not a straw man.

01:04:17.760 --> 01:04:18.520
It's just Hegel.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:29.060
Yeah, just using Hegel as a figure for a dangerous kind of thinking is sort of the shared project of Derrida, Deleuze, and Foucault.

01:04:29.160 --> 01:04:31.700
Now, they all have kind of different ways of dealing with it.

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:46.060
Like, Derrida, for example, wants to pass through Hegel in a sort of Aufhebung of the dialectic, where he kind of intensifies it and reads Hegel carefully, warns of the danger of Hegel, and ultimately wants to do something else.

01:04:46.060 --> 01:04:58.820
Whereas with Deleuze, Hegel represents the most dangerous ethical and political kind of thinking or kind of living, and that needs to be completely eradicated.

01:04:59.300 --> 01:04:59.380
Right?

01:04:59.480 --> 01:05:00.580
So it's a more—

01:05:00.580 --> 01:05:01.520
No, no, no.

01:05:01.580 --> 01:05:02.640
In Nietzsche—no, no, no.

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:06.100
But I'm saying, like, it's a more polemical response, which serves different purposes.

01:05:06.260 --> 01:05:07.680
I'm not critiquing Deleuze here.

01:05:07.820 --> 01:05:11.700
I'm just saying the way he mobilizes Hegel, Hegel is the enemy.

01:05:11.960 --> 01:05:14.240
I mean, at least in, like, Nietzsche and Philosophy.

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:14.800
Right.

01:05:15.060 --> 01:05:20.120
Hegel sees Nietzsche seeing—or Deleuze sees Nietzsche seeing Hegel as the enemy.

01:05:20.240 --> 01:05:21.740
I mean, I agree with that.

01:05:22.040 --> 01:05:22.180
Right.

01:05:22.180 --> 01:05:30.900
But in that sense, I mean, you know, it's always more complicated than that, and the relationships among them, even in that book, are not simply opposed to Hegel.

01:05:30.900 --> 01:05:37.940
And that's where I think it's really great, like, what he says about negative theology, you know, you gave that example, Nathaniel, is really great.

01:05:38.020 --> 01:05:40.260
It's like, look, there will be times where—what does he say?

01:05:40.300 --> 01:05:46.380
It approximates negative theology to the point of being indistinguishable, right?

01:05:46.680 --> 01:05:48.340
Yeah, this is on page six.

01:05:48.880 --> 01:05:49.060
Right.

01:05:49.180 --> 01:05:58.880
So it will—so much so that the detours, locutions, and syntax in which I will take recourse will resemble those of negative theology, occasionally even to the point of being indistinguishable from negative theology.

01:05:59.180 --> 01:06:01.580
You know, and that's, to me, that's a big claim.

01:06:01.760 --> 01:06:06.460
In other words, like, I'm not simply different than this thing that differentiates me.

01:06:06.880 --> 01:06:10.980
And there are places in this discourse where it's just—it's going to be like that.

01:06:11.280 --> 01:06:13.120
I am trying to do some—

01:06:13.120 --> 01:06:13.280
Right.

01:06:13.380 --> 01:06:17.820
I'm trying to do something else other than that sort of sense of super-essentiality of God.

01:06:18.220 --> 01:06:19.600
You know, I'm trying to do something else.

01:06:19.660 --> 01:06:23.720
But there's nothing about, like, one can always pretend that it makes no difference, right?

01:06:23.780 --> 01:06:25.440
One can always act as if, not pretend.

01:06:26.080 --> 01:06:33.860
And yet, those aspects of difference, which are thereby delineated, are not theological, not even in the order of the most negative of negative theologies,

01:06:33.860 --> 01:06:52.940
which are always concerned with disengaging a super-essentiality behind the finite categories of essence and existence, that is, of presence, and always hastening to recall that God has refused the predicate of existence only in order to acknowledge his superior, inconceivable, and ineffable mode of being.

01:06:53.260 --> 01:06:57.980
Such a development is not in question here, and this will be confirmed progressively.

01:06:57.980 --> 01:07:12.280
Difference is not only irreducible to any ontological or theological-ontotheological reappropriation, but as the very opening of the space in which ontotheology, philosophy, produces its system and its history.

01:07:12.680 --> 01:07:17.400
It includes ontotheology, inscribing it and exceeding it within return.

01:07:17.400 --> 01:07:34.420
I mean, that's a pretty key difference is, like, at least in its most common understandings, a negative theology is basically trying to say, like, look, the finitude of all of these concepts fail to get at the super-essentiality of God.

01:07:34.420 --> 01:07:46.580
It's like, you know, it's like, we're not just, this is the ontological distinction, is that, like, God is the beingness of being, not just, like, a particular being.

01:07:46.580 --> 01:07:58.120
So we can only negatively approximate it by sort of, like, you know, using our finite concepts to, you know, gesture toward this super-essential being.

01:07:58.120 --> 01:08:09.860
And one gets, and from that, one gets all of the nostalgia of Heidegger, one gets, you know, like, everything, the desire for meaning, the desire, like, all of that stuff is, but that's where, to me, that sentence is so great.

01:08:09.940 --> 01:08:26.060
Like, I wrote a similar sentence in the definitions of rhetoric thing, which is, difference is not only irreducible to any ontological or theological reappropriation, but it is only materialized through its, through those reappropriations, right?

01:08:26.060 --> 01:08:31.240
Like, in other words, it's irreducible to them, and it's not troubled by that fact, right?

01:08:31.240 --> 01:08:39.820
Like, it's, so it doesn't matter whether you can, and in fact, you can only have, you would say, you can only have ontological and theological reappropriations, right?

01:08:40.300 --> 01:08:56.040
Well, that's such a key, that's such a key part of this definition of difference that I feel like is often lost in its appropriation or interpretation, where it's like that dual, it's not only the condition of possibility for life in general.

01:08:56.060 --> 01:09:05.420
For God, for God, for the essence of things, it's also the condition of possibility for thinking the essence, which is, that's the only way you get to the thing, right?

01:09:05.460 --> 01:09:16.460
So it's like, all of the attempts to locate, difference, or trace as not just a category, but as an ontological thingness, right?

01:09:16.700 --> 01:09:22.740
It forgets that second part where it's like, no, no, no, it's also caught up in this movement of appropriation.

01:09:23.080 --> 01:09:24.320
It's not the single...

01:09:24.320 --> 01:09:26.280
But I want to insist on this for you, Boo-Boo.

01:09:26.420 --> 01:09:28.080
It can't not forget that.

01:09:28.480 --> 01:09:31.100
There's no option of keeping that in mind, right?

01:09:31.140 --> 01:09:36.220
It has to forget that, because that's not something that is a present thought that one can maintain.

01:09:36.860 --> 01:09:38.640
It's not like, you know what I mean?

01:09:38.720 --> 01:09:43.140
Like, the fact that it's constantly failing is the sign of its success.

01:09:44.040 --> 01:09:44.240
Right.

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:45.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:09:45.060 --> 01:09:50.640
I mean, it wouldn't be a failed interpretation, like, to say that the trace is originary.

01:09:50.760 --> 01:09:52.180
And it's not wrong, right?

01:09:52.220 --> 01:09:53.200
No, no, it's not wrong.

01:09:53.700 --> 01:09:54.000
You know?

01:09:54.140 --> 01:09:54.720
Because, I mean...

01:09:54.720 --> 01:10:04.960
I mean, the thing that I end up thinking in regard to that is, it just goes in kind of predictable directions, and I understand how that thing works, and it's not very interesting to me.

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:07.020
That's the best that I can mobilize.

01:10:07.440 --> 01:10:16.660
But that doesn't mean it's not interesting to other people and doesn't do lots of really cool work, and that someone else can actualize a differential component within those things, of course.

01:10:16.720 --> 01:10:17.700
Right, right.

01:10:17.700 --> 01:10:22.980
But to me, you know, the logic of difference can easily...

01:10:22.980 --> 01:10:37.500
I mean, this is why, to return to what we were talking about before, one of the reasons, and I think this is big, and I had a hard time with this for years, why Derrida insists that we not attempt to save Nietzsche from the Nazi appropriations, which is what Heidegger attempts to do, right?

01:10:37.560 --> 01:10:44.680
And he's like, no, it's really important that he's not simply capable of, but was appropriated that way, right?

01:10:44.680 --> 01:10:50.300
Like, that's important, because he is also, that does, this line of thinking does also go there.

01:10:50.480 --> 01:10:52.160
It really, genuinely does.

01:10:52.360 --> 01:10:56.700
So it's not like, let's protect him from this thing by cordoning it off.

01:11:14.680 --> 01:11:27.580
I'll see you next time.
